{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_011eDxqNEVaZnhFWikhwtrRa","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have all the information I need to analyze the failure. Let me understand the issue:\n\n**Input file: \"Faszerowana papryka.real.txt\"**\n- Line 1: `Faszerowana papryka` (expected title - Polish, mixed case)\n- Line 2: `PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM` (ALL_CAPS - Korean dish romanization)\n- Line 3: `파프리카 계란찜` (Korean characters)\n- Line 4+: Polish recipe text\n\n**Expected:** `Faszerowana papryka`\n**Got:** `PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM`\n\n\nThe algorithm's bilingual title detection is checking for a non-capitalized title at position 0, then filtering out all-caps entries if there's exactly one and it appears early in the file. But the logic is incomplete—it's not properly excluding the all-caps Korean romanization when deciding which title to return. Checking if \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" actually passes the hard filters that would allow it to be detected as a candidate in the first place. The vowel ratio checks out at about 35%, which falls within the acceptable range, and the text doesn't exhibit any other garbling indicators. \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" clears all the hard filters and qualifies as a candidate, so now I'm moving into the bilingual detection phase.\n\nI need to verify whether \"Faszerowana papryka\" passes the hard filters too. Starting with the garbling check—it begins with an uppercase F, and counting through the vowels in the Polish text, I'm getting around 8 vowels total, which I need to evaluate against the ratio thresholds. with y treated as vowel in the regex `[^aeiouAEIOUyYąęóĄĘÓ]`)\n    - Total letters: 18\n    - Vowel ratio: 8/18 ≈ 0.44 ✓\n  - No \". \" pattern ✓\n  - Starts with uppercase ✓\n  - Two words, no short lowercase word ✓\n- Not garbled ✓\n\nNow, does `prePos0` match \"Faszerowana papryka\"?\n- `scored.find((s) => s.position === 0 && !isAllCaps(s.text))` \n- \"Faszerowana papryka\" is at position 0 (line index 0 in the original lines) ✓\n- Not ALL_CAPS ✓\n\nSo `prePos0` should find it. Now I'm checking how many ALL_CAPS candidates exist in `preAllCaps` — \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" at position 1 qualifies, and \"NA 3 PAPRYKI\" from line 5 also passes the hard filters since it doesn't start with a number and falls within the length constraints. NA 3 PAPRYKI\" would pass hard filters probably\n  - isAllCaps: letters = \"NAPAPRYKI\" all upper ✓\n- What about \"SKŁADNIKI\" (line 10)? Letters = \"SKADNIKI\" all uppercase (Polish letter Ł is removed). isAllCaps would return true.\n- What about \"Przygotowanie\" (line 7)? Mixed case, not ALL_CAPS.\n- What about \"WARZYWA\" (line 26 end)? ALL_CAPS.\n\nSo there might be multiple ALL_CAPS candidates: \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\", \"NA 3 PAPRYKI\", \"SKŁADNIKI\", \"WARZYWA\".\n\nThe bilingual detection condition is `preAllCaps.length === 1` - if there are multiple ALL_CAPS candidates, this condition fails and the bilingual suppression never activates. That's the core issue. The document has several ALL_CAPS strings scattered throughout—the Korean romanization, serving size notation, and section headers—so the algorithm doesn't recognize it as bilingual and instead applies normal scoring, where \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" gets boosted by the ALL_CAPS bonus. I'm checking whether \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" passes the structural heading requirements—it's all caps with two words, and both \"PAPRIKA\" and \"GYERAN-JJIM\" have at least 4 letters, so it clears that threshold unlike \"NA 3 PAPRYKI\" which fails because \"NA\" is too short.\n\nNow testing single-word cases like \"SKŁADNIKI\" and \"WARZYWA\"—both fail the word count requirement since they need at least 2 words to be considered structural headings.\n\nSo \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" is the only structural heading and gets both bonuses. For the bilingual detection, I'm checking if there's exactly one ALL_CAPS candidate in the first two positions, which would indicate a language switch. Looking at \"SKŁADNIKI\" now to see if it's garbled by examining its letter composition and vowel distribution. = 3, total = 9, ratio = 3/9 = 0.33 ✓\n- passesHardFilters: yes ✓\n\nSo `preAllCaps` has multiple candidates, which means the bilingual detection condition fails since it requires exactly 1 ALL_CAPS candidate. This document has several section headers in all caps (\"SKŁADNIKI\", \"WARZYWA\", \"NA 3 PAPRYKI\") alongside the Korean romanization \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\", so the algorithm picks the latter instead of \"Faszerowana papryka\" because the condition `preAllCaps.length ===\n\n` 1 fails. Without suppression, \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" wins due to its ALL_CAPS bonus (+0.08) and structural heading bonus (+0.10) plus position advantage, while \"Faszerowana papryka\" at position 0 only gets the position factor.\n\nNow I'm checking the burst detection logic in buildCandidates—specifically whether \"Faszerowana papryka\" with length 20 gets filtered out since the check requires length < 20 and isLikelyGarbled.\n\nSince \"Faszerowana papryka\" is exactly 20 characters, it doesn't meet the strict less-than condition, so the burst detection loop stops immediately and the line gets included as a candidate from position 0. Let me trace through the scoring more carefully to confirm why \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" ends up winning.\n\nFor \"Faszerowana papryka\" at position 0, the rawScore gets multiplied by a positionFactor of about 1.12 since it's at the start, plus no all-caps or structural bonuses. For \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" at position 1, the positionFactor is closer to 1.0 since it's further down the list, which means despite being all-caps, the earlier position advantage for the first candidate gets outweighed by other scoring factors. + 0.12 * (1 - 0.077) ≈ 1.0 + 0.111 ≈ 1.11\n- allCapsBonus = 0.08\n- structuralBonus = 0.10 (it's the firstStructuralHeading)\n- score ≈ rawScore * 1.11 + 0.08 + 0.10 = rawScore * 1.11 + 0.18\n\nSo \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" gets a huge +0.18 bonus from being ALL_CAPS + structural heading, while \"Faszerowana papryka\" gets nothing beyond the position factor. Even if \"Faszerowana papryka\" has better raw embedding similarity, the +0.18 bonus for \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" likely outweighs it. The bilingual suppression doesn't kick in because there are multiple ALL_CAPS lines throughout the document—section headers like SKŁADNIKI and WARZYWA prevent the condition from triggering, so the scoring bonus stands unchecked.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":10103,"cache_read_input_tokens":19686,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":10103},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"05e663a7-2814-4721-a7b5-7c4e35d15ae3","uuid":"31c1605a-0ad1-4037-959a-47071fc0d6b6"}
